You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput Spring Boot application experiences a gradual memory leak in the JVM Heap, eventually leading to an `OutOfMemoryError`. The heap dump reveals thousands of `OrderContext` instances retained by Tomcat container threads. You trace the leak to the following service class implementation:

java
@Service
public class OrderProcessingService {
    private static final ThreadLocal<OrderContext> context = new ThreadLocal<>();

    public void processOrder(Order order) {
        context.set(new OrderContext(order));
        CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> {
            enrichOrder(context.get()); 
        }).thenRun(() -> {
            context.remove();
        });
    } 

    private void enrichOrder(OrderContext ctx) {
        // Heavy business logic
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where an enterprise Spring Boot application experiences a slow memory leak and high GC pause times. The JVM heap dump reveals millions of managed Hibernate entities and associated `StatefulPersistenceContext` instances. You trace the root cause to the following scheduled task implementation:

java
@Component
public class BatchReportScheduler {

    @Autowired
    private ReportProcessor reportProcessor;

    @Scheduled(fixedDelay = 10000)
    @Transactional
    public void executePendingTasks() {
        List<ReportTask> pendingTasks = reportProcessor.fetchPendingTasks();
        for (ReportTask task : pendingTasks) {
            reportProcessor.processSingleTask(task);
        }
    }
}
